# MR Review Skill

Run a comprehensive, multi-dimensional review of a GitLab merge request by dispatching specialized sub-agents in parallel.

## Overview

This skill orchestrates up to 10 specialized review agents, each analyzing a different dimension of an MR's changes. Agents run in parallel for speed and return structured findings that are synthesized into a single summary.

### Review Dimensions

| # | Dimension | Agent | When Triggered |
|---|-----------|-------|----------------|
| 1 | Security | `review-security` | **Always** (all MRs) |
| 2 | Database (PostgreSQL) | `review-database` | `db/`, `lib/gitlab/background_migration/`, migration helpers |
| 3 | ClickHouse | `review-clickhouse` | `ee/app/models/click_house/`, `ee/db/click_house/`, `lib/click_house/` |
| 4 | Performance & Scalability | `review-performance` | `app/models/`, `app/services/`, `app/controllers/`, `lib/api/`, `app/workers/` |
| 5 | Quality Assurance | `review-qa` | `spec/`, `ee/spec/`, `qa/` |
| 6 | Frontend | `review-frontend` | `*.vue`, `*.js`, `*.ts`, `app/assets/javascripts/`, `*.haml` |
| 7 | Backend Architecture | `review-backend` | `app/models/`, `app/services/`, `app/controllers/`, `app/finders/`, `app/workers/`, `lib/` |
| 8 | Documentation | `review-docs` | `doc/`, changelog trailers, `locale/` |
| 9 | Analytics Instrumentation | `review-analytics` | `config/events/`, `config/metrics/`, `ee/config/metrics/` |
| 10 | GraphQL | `review-graphql` | `app/graphql/`, `ee/app/graphql/` |

## Workflow

Follow these steps exactly:

### Step 1: Determine the MR

- If the user provided a project and MR IID (e.g., "review gitlab-org/gitlab!12345"), use those directly.
- If only an IID was given, default the project to `gitlab-org/gitlab`.
- If no MR was specified, try to infer from the current branch using `git rev-parse --abbrev-ref HEAD`.

### Step 2: Fetch MR data

Use GitLab MCP tools to gather the full context:

1. **Metadata**: `gitlab_get_merge_request` with `include_changes: true` — get title, author, description, labels, changed file list with stats.
2. **Full diff**: `gitlab_list_merge_request_diffs` — paginate if needed (use `per_page: 100`, follow pages) to get the complete diff for all changed files.

Both calls can be made in parallel.

### Step 3: Classify changed files

Categorize every changed file path into one or more review dimensions using these rules:

| File Pattern | Dimensions |
|---|---|
| `db/migrate/`, `db/post_migrate/`, `db/structure.sql`, `lib/gitlab/database/`, `lib/gitlab/background_migration/` | Database |
| `ee/app/models/click_house/`, `ee/db/click_house/`, `lib/click_house/`, files with `ClickHouse` in name | ClickHouse |
| `app/models/`, `app/services/`, `app/finders/`, `app/workers/`, `app/controllers/`, `lib/api/`, `lib/gitlab/` | Backend, Performance, Security |
| `app/graphql/`, `ee/app/graphql/` | GraphQL, Backend |
| `app/assets/javascripts/`, `ee/app/assets/javascripts/`, `*.vue`, `*.js`, `*.ts` | Frontend |
| `app/views/`, `ee/app/views/`, `*.haml` | Frontend, Backend (if contains Ruby logic) |
| `spec/`, `ee/spec/`, `qa/` | QA |
| `doc/`, `locale/` | Docs |
| `config/events/`, `config/metrics/`, `ee/config/metrics/`, `ee/config/events/` | Analytics |
| `ee/` mirrors of any above | Same dimensions + EE/CE separation (Backend) |
| **All files** | Security (always runs) |

A dimension is **triggered** if at least one changed file matches its patterns.

### Step 4: Dispatch agents in parallel

For each triggered dimension, launch a `task()` call with:
- `subagent_type`: the agent name (e.g., `"review-security"`)
- `description`: `"MR !{iid} — {dimension} review"`
- `prompt`: A structured prompt containing:

```
## MR Context
- **MR**: !{iid} — {title}
- **Project**: {project_path}
- **Author**: {author}
- **Description**: {description (first 500 chars)}
- **Labels**: {labels}
- **Changed files**: {count} files (+{insertions} −{deletions})

## Files in your scope
{list of files relevant to this dimension with their change stats}

## Diffs to review
{the actual diff content for files in scope — include the full diff, do not truncate}
```

**IMPORTANT**: Launch ALL agent tasks in the same message to maximize parallelism. Do NOT wait for one agent before dispatching the next.

**IMPORTANT**: Only include diffs relevant to each agent's scope. Do not send the entire MR diff to every agent — filter by the file classification from Step 3.

### Step 5: Collect results and render summary

Wait for all agents to return. Then render the structured output described below.

## Output Format

Render the review as follows:

```markdown
# MR Review: !{iid} — {title}

**Project:** {project}  |  **Author:** {author}  |  **Files changed:** {N} (+{ins} −{del})

## Summary

| Dimension | Verdict | Findings |
|-----------|---------|----------|
| 🔒 Security | {verdict} | {count} |
| 🗄️ Database | {verdict} | {count} |
| 🏛️ ClickHouse | {verdict} | {count} |
| ⚡ Performance | {verdict} | {count} |
| 🧪 QA | {verdict} | {count} |
| 🎨 Frontend | {verdict} | {count} |
| 📐 Backend | {verdict} | {count} |
| 📝 Docs | {verdict} | {count} |
| 📊 Analytics | {verdict} | {count} |
| 🔷 GraphQL | {verdict} | {count} |

## Detailed Findings

### {emoji} {Dimension}
{agent's findings, preserving severity/location/suggestion format}

...repeat for each dimension with findings...

## Dimensions Skipped
- {emoji} {Dimension} — {reason, e.g., "No JS/Vue/HAML files changed"}
```

**Verdict values:**
- `✅ Pass` — No issues found
- `⚠️ Warnings` — Low/Medium severity findings only
- `🚨 Issues` — High/Critical severity findings present
- `⏭️ Skipped` — Dimension not triggered (no relevant files changed)

## Agent Guidelines

1. **Always fetch the full diff** — Use `gitlab_list_merge_request_diffs` with pagination; never review just metadata or file names
2. **Skip irrelevant dimensions** — If no files match a dimension's patterns, mark it "Skipped" rather than dispatching an agent
3. **Provide full diff context to each agent** — Each agent receives the diffs for files in its scope, not just file names
4. **Maximize parallelism** — Dispatch ALL selected agents in a single message with multiple `task()` calls
5. **Severity levels** — Agents use `[Critical]`, `[High]`, `[Medium]`, `[Low]`, `[Info]` consistently
6. **Constructive feedback** — Every finding must include a concrete suggestion or fix
7. **Cite line numbers** — Reference specific files and line numbers, not vague descriptions
8. **Respect scope** — Each agent stays in its lane; don't duplicate findings across dimensions
9. **Handle large MRs** — If an MR has 50+ files, still provide the full relevant diffs to each agent; the per-agent scope filtering keeps individual prompts manageable
